Notes:
The summary from the Connecticut DOT - Building Inspection Report dated 7/19/2019 provides an overall rating of 3.96, as follows:

The Southeast Area Transit building was constructed in 1982 and has had only minor renovations
since, including a roof replacement in 2012. The building is a single story occupied structure
consisting of a large bus storage area, a large bus maintenance area, a bus wash bay, a dispatch
area and other office and support spaces. The building is a combination of pre-engineered steel
and standard steel construction. The exterior is finished with vertical metal panels and brick
masonry, and has white, EPDM membrane roofing. Heating is provided throughout the entire
building and air conditioning is provided only in the office, dispatch and other support spaces. The
building is equipped with a sprinkler system, a fire alarm system, and a 100% standby emergency
generator. The building is connected city water, but not to natural gas or city sewer. Sanitary
systems are provided by way of a septic tank and leaching fields. This site also includes a motor
fuel island for fueling.
SUMMARY OF INSPECTION RESULTS:
AVERAGE EMPLOYEE HEALTH/WELLNESS RATING: 4.38
AVERAGE BUILDING STATE OF GOOD REPAIR RATING: 3.53
OVERALL BUILDING/STRUCTURE RATING: 3.96

Agency Name: New York City Department of Transportation
Notes: The Whitehall Terminal is a 207,000 sq-ft intermodal terminal that incorporates foot passenger, ferry, rail rapid transit, bus, taxi, and auto transit modes as well as significant indoor and outdoor public spaces. The terminal building incorporates three slips for the Staten Island Ferry service and a new headhouse entrance for the (1)   subway station, as well as waiting and circulation spaces, concession (store) spaces, maintenance and operational spaces, limited office space, outdoor viewing decks, and spaces housing the equipment needed to operate the ferry slip transfer bridges, as well as incidental services spaces

Agency Name: New York City Department of Transportation
Private Modes Served: Shared With Non-Public Mode: Private Water Transit
Notes: The St. George Ferry Terminal located in Staten Island was constructed in 1948-50, with major remodeling and alterations undertaken between 2001-05.  The building is a structure incorporating a ferry terminal with four ferry slips and associated transfer bridges, waiting and circulation spaces, ferry operational, dispatch, crew, and ancillary spaces, a commuter rail station and rail yard, a roof top bus terminal, concession spaces, commuter parking and vehicle circulation structures, and ancillary buildings and structures, all situated on a 7 acre site.

Agency Name: New York City Department of Transportation
Facility Type: Combined Administrative and Maintenance Facility (describe in Notes)
Notes: The Ferry Maintenance Facility houses personnel key to ferry operations as well as spare parts and equipment that keep the ferries running safely and efficiently. The FMF is the base of operations serving as a repair yard and a repository for plans, specs, and parts. It is a brick structure 85,000 sq feet in size built in 1992.

Agency Name: New York City Department of Transportation
Notes: BMB Slip 5 provides berths to ferry boats on the East River. Service is provided by NY Waterway for transportation to and from New Jersey. There are two ferry berths that can accommodate bow and side loading ferries and a covered waiting area. The landing is close to numerous bus and subway locations, other ferry piers and terminals, major residential and business districts and has a bike share station adjacent to its entrance.

Agency Name: New York City Department of Transportation
Notes: The East 34th Street Ferry Landing in Midtown Manhattan provides slips to ferries on the East River.  Service is provided by NYC Ferry and other private operators. There are covered ticketing and waiting areas and five ferry berths. The landing is close to numerous bus, subway and commuter rail connections, major residential and business districts and has a bike share station on site.

Agency Name: New York City Department of Transportation
Facility Name: Pier 11 Wall Street Ferry Landing Slips B, D South Side
Notes: The Pier 11 Wall Street Ferry Landing in East Lower Manhattan provides slips to ferries on the East River.  Service is provided by NYC Ferry and other private operators. There are covered ticketing and waiting areas and ten ferry berths. The landing is close to numerous bus, subway and commuter rail connections, major residential and business districts and has a bike share station on site.

Facility heavily damaged by hurricane IAN on 9/28/22.
**************
LeeTran's Beach Park and Ride was classified as a Category 2 based on the significant damage to the facility and the roadways leading to the facility that resulted from Hurricane Ian on September 28, 2022, that caused the facility to close.  LeeTran re-evaluated the facility in October 2023 and reclassified it at a Category 3 based on the limited amenities (i.e. communications, pedestrian information system outages, etc.) and will continue to work towards meeting the standards of Category 4 which is the level of that station prior to the hurricane damage.

Sponsor Name: Puerto Rico Highway and Transportation Authority
Notes:
Since 1986, when the public transportation Terminal Carlos Garay, began to operate, the house beside the terminal became the administrative office of the terminal, function which currently holds. This office operates within an ancient structure that is part of the historic area of Ponce. This office is located between Victoria and Union Streets, and is part of Carlos Garay Terminal. It is considered as a historical value structure by the State Historical Preservation Office (SHPO). Since 2011 the municipality requested the opinion of SHPO for the rehabilitation process. After SHPO Office reviewed the documentation determined that the office is a historic property.
The original facade of the property dated from the years 1890 to 1900.

Facility Type: Combined Administrative and Maintenance Facility (describe in Notes)
Notes: This facility is the primary office and maintenance space for DMT operations.  The condition assessment was downgraded to 3 after the June 2021 assessment during the COVID closures.  A feasibility study was done to determine what upgrades would need to be done in order to make our facility more "pandemic friendly".  We had to close our customer counter because of the inability to distance ourselves and customers from one another.  We also have very limited facilities for our drivers to prepare for their day, eat lunch, or sit and relax.  Our administrative offices are small and do not allow for any type of meeting without broaching the 6' distance.  The study has determined that changes need to be made in all of these areas.  With the addition of new buses this past year, there is a need for more room to park buses.  Some have to be left in the washbay and the service bay at night due to lack of parking.  There are many upgrades that could be done as well and we have a state capital grant to complete some of the work needed right away in the back.

Facility Name: P-MAX PKG 4  Level Boarding Transit Center (2019)
Notes:
In December of 2019, the KCATA went live with 19 level boarding stops  for the Package 4 installation of the Prospect Max BRT project and 51 total stops.

There are 19 total that are located along the Prospect Max corridor, which ranges from 12th and Prospect Avenue to 75th and Prospect Avenue, a major BRT line.  

Only two of these stops  we believe are attributable to the NTD definition of Passenger Stations, despite a few attempts to nail down this definition.  The kiosks along this project are most dual sides and many have markers, power, and other amenities.

This entry is for the Passenger Station Transit Center at 12th and Charlotte (aka East Village Transit Center).  This center features a local post with real time video display; a double-sided free standing kiosk; a standing building; 8 double-sided exterior signs; 2 cradle point routers; along with other features.

Facility Name: P-MAX PKG 4 Level Boarding Stations "Alpha Pointe"  TC (2019)
Notes:
In December of 2019, the KCATA went live with 19 level boarding passenger stations for the Package 4 installation of the Prospect Max BRT project.  

There are 19 total that are located along the Prospect Max corridor, which ranges from 12th and Prospect Avenue to 75th and Prospect Avenue, a major BRT line.  

This entry is for the Passenger Station only at 75th and Prospect which went live in December of 2019.  This has a free standing building, 2 local posts with real time video display; 2 double-side freestanding kiosks; 7 exterior displays; a cradle point router; 5 conductive bays; among other features.

Facility Name: Southern Teton Area Rapid Transit Garage
Notes:
Approx. 43k sq. foot metal building with metal siding and roof. 
* 5 Large garage doors on S end of Bldg.
* Floor drains on S end of bldg and in middle area of bays. 
* East side of Building has three rooms to be accessed from exterior of building - large Elect. room, large Generator Room(currently empty, when the next phase of building is completed the room will be completed with equipment) and large Fire Sprinkler room
* Entering the 5 bays there is a long entry way for buses to be serviced with fluids. Also a driveway between wash bay and bus servicing area. 
* Large wash bay with automatic bus wash. 
* Off main garage floor is a Fluids room. Contains an air compressor, all the fluids for bus servicing and wash bay fluids and recirculation. 
* Garage floor has radiant heat (water) as well as overhead heat,
* Off main garage floor is a server room, housing server equipment, fire suppression controller and heater server/controller. 
* Office area consists of three offices, one bathroom and one open area with cabinets and sink. 
* One entry way from main garage to office area serves as Fair Box room.
* Roof has approx. 200 solar panels, Also half of the roof serves as a "Green Roof" consisting of grass and rocks providing a nice aesthetic view for residents looking down on garage.

This is the older protion of garage. Steve advised HVAC system has issues. Metal building. Large kitchen area with two offices and bathroom. Office/ training room upstairs with AC closet and storage area. Steve also advised some lighting issues. 6 bay garage with washbay. New roof in 2015. New siding and exterior lights.

The facility is located on a 4.4-acre site at the southwest corner of Rickenbacker Place and Rutan Court in the airport area of Livermore. The facility consists of a 27,365 S.F., single story, and concrete tilt-up building.  The maximum building height is 24’6”.

The administration area of the building contains 6,835 S.F. of floor space and includes an entrance lobby, reception area, community/board room, restrooms, private offices, conference room, lunchroom, file room and a general workroom.

The operations area contains 4,697 S.F. of floor space and includes fixed route and paratransit dispatch areas, drivers’ room, drivers’ locker area, restrooms, vending machine area, private offices, conference room and semi-private accounting offices.

The maintenance area contains 16,103 S.F. and includes a chassis wash (with high pressure steam clean system), an inspection bay (with recessed pit), two general repair bays, a general shop area, lubrication room, battery room, parts storage room, lead mechanic area, parts clerk and maintenance manager’s offices, mechanics’ lunch room, locker rooms, restrooms and showers. Included in this area are overhead delivery lines for lubricants and other fluids
Site improvements include a diesel fueling island (two dispensers and three 10,000 gallon underground diesel storage tanks), a bus washer, concrete parking area for approximately 40 route buses and 4 “bad order” buses, salvage and garbage dumpster areas and asphalt paving for 85 employee and visitor parking spaces.

Incidental to building and site improvements are the installation and construction of a waste oil tank, oil/water separators, underground site utilities, building mechanical and electrical systems, site lighting, perimeter fencing and landscaping.
This facility currently has a fuel and wash on it, storage, and parking. Some day it will have an admin and maintenance building as well.

Notes: Salesforce Transit Center located in San Francisco, CA is a ground-up, Type I concrete and steel transportation and recreation project. The project is designed by Pelli Clarke Pelli Architects. This CM-GC project totals 1,162,700 square feet throughout one structure with four levels above grade and two levels below grade.  The Salesforce Transit Center replaces the former Transbay Terminal at First and Mission Streets with a modern regional transit hub connecting eight Bay area counties and the state of California through 11 transit systems: AC Transit, BART, Caltrain, Golden Gate Transit, Greyhound, Muni, SamTrans, WestCAT Lynx, Amtrak, Paratransit and future High Speed Rail from San Francisco to Los Angeles/Anaheim. Bus access to the transit center is provided via a cable stay bridge which connects the Bay Bridge to the Transit Center’s elevated bus deck level.
